{{for|non-fiction imprint of Penguin Books|Pelican Books}} {{Refimprove|date=October 2014}} {{Infobox publisher | image = Pelican_Publishing_Company_logo.jpg | parent = | status = | founded = 1926 | founder = John McClure | successor = | country = [[United States]] | headquarters = [[Gretna, Louisiana]] | distribution = [[United States]] and worldwide | keypeople = | publications = [[Book]]s | topics = [[history]], [[travel guides]], [[art]], [[architecture]], [[children's books]], [[textbooks]], [[Louisiana]] | genre = | imprints = | revenue = | numemployees = | nasdaq = | url = {{URL|http://pelicanpub.com}} }}
'''Pelican Publishing Company''' is a [[book publisher]] based in [[Gretna, Louisiana|Gretna]], a suburb of [[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]]. Formed in 1926, Pelican is the largest independent trade book publisher located in the [[U.S. South]].{{Citation Needed|date=April 2017}} Pelican publishes approximately 60 titles per year and maintains a backlist of over 2500 books.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Herman|first1=Jeff|title=Herman's Guide to Book Publishers, Editors, & Literary Agents|date=2012|publisher=Sourcebooks, Inc.|location=Naperville, IL|isbn=9781402260612|page=269}}</ref> Most of its titles relate to [[Louisiana]] and [[Southern culture]], [[Southern cuisine|cuisine]], art, travel guides, [[history]], children's books, and textbooks.
==History== Formed in 1926 by John McClure, Pelican was tied early in its history to [[William Faulkner]] and Stuart O. Landry. In 1970, Dr. [[Milburn E. Calhoun]] and family acquired Pelican. Calhoun served as company president and publisher prior to his death in 2012. Since his passing, daughter Kathleen Calhoun Nettleton has occupied his place as publisher and president.
==Significant titles== Pelican Publishing Company has produced many noteworthy titles, including the following:
*''[[Arnaud's]] Restaurant Cookbook: Legendary Creole Cuisine'' by [[Kit Wohl]]. *''Blood in West Virginia: Brumfield v. McCoy'' by Brandon Ray Kirk, which tells the story of the [[Lincoln County Feud]].<ref>{{cite web | first1=Brandon | last1=Kirk | url=http://www.pelicanpub.com/proddetail.php?prod=9781455619184#.VJ0980CABg | title=Blood in West Virginia: Brumfield v. McCoy | publisher=Pelican Publishing Company | accessdate=26 December 2014 | website=pelicanpub.com}}</ref> *''[[The Cajun Night Before Christmas]]'' by James Rice: A [[parody]] of the popular [[The Night Before Christmas|Night Before Christmas]] poem in which Santa Claus visits [[Cajun]] Louisiana. *''The Cavalry Battle that Saved the Union: Custer vs. Stuart at Gettysburg'', Paul D. Walker, Pelican Publishing Company, Gretna, LA, 2002 *''Clovis Crawfish'', a children's series by Mary Alice Fontenot *''The Commissioner: A True Story of Deceit, Dishonor, and Death'', [[Bill Keith (Louisiana politician)|Bill Keith]] study of the [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]] public safety commissioner [[George W. D'Artois]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NvpN1t9TMrgC&pg=PA28&lpg=PA28&dq=Sheriff+Harold+Terry+of+Caddo+Parish&source=bl&ots=FLpFpz8sBI&sig=CiYKwwaCvjQP3tfXSYdiOVQqKZc&hl=en&sa=X&ei=aaccVJbbIpSgyATF5oFg&ved=0CDUQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Sheriff%20Harold%20Terry%20of%20Caddo%20Parish&f=false|title=The Commissioner: A True Story of Deceit, Dishonor, and Death|author=Bill Keith|publisher=Pelican Publishing Company|location=[[Gretna, Louisiana|Gretna]], [[Louisiana]]|date=2009|isbn=978-1-58980-655-9|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> *''[[Finn McCool's Football Club]]'' by Stephen Rea, released February 2009. Memoir of the author's experiences at an [[Irish pub]] in [[New Orleans]] and what happened to the patrons before, during, and after [[Hurricane Katrina]]. *''[[Louisiana Almanac]]'' (series): A resource of statistical data and historical information related to the [[State of Louisiana]]. *''The Maverick Guide'' (series): A series of travel guides begun by Robert W. Bone (author). *''New Orleans Classic Cookbook Series featuring Desserts, Appetizers, Seafood and Gumbos & Soups'', also by [[Kit Wohl]] *''See You at the Top'', the first book by motivational business speaker [[Zig Ziglar]] *''Sherwood Anderson and Other Famous Creoles'' by [[William Faulkner]]: The first trade publication written by [[William Faulkner]]. *''The South Was Right!'' by James Ronald Kennedy and Walter Donald Kennedy: A controversial historical perspective that argues that the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]] had the right to secede from the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]].
